1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,014
The goal of this level is to train people to differentiate beats by BPM.

2
00:00:03,014 --> 00:00:04,521
There are three groups of flowers here.

3
00:00:04,521 --> 00:00:06,028
Each group beats at a particular rate.

4
00:00:06,028 --> 00:00:08,396
When activated, the flower plays a loop at that rate once,

5
00:00:08,396 --> 00:00:09,903
and its orb blinks at that BPM.

6
00:00:09,903 --> 00:00:11,626
If another flower is activated during that playback,

7
00:00:11,626 --> 00:00:13,779
it plays after the current one, and both play together.

8
00:00:13,779 --> 00:00:14,640
If the BPMs match,

9
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:17,223
another flower can be added to the group during that time; otherwise,

10
00:00:17,223 --> 00:00:18,084
the player starts over.

11
00:00:18,084 --> 00:00:20,452
Game audio didn't get recorded in the Mac OS screen recording,

12
00:00:20,452 --> 00:00:21,744
so leaving that to your imagination.

13
00:00:21,744 --> 00:00:24,112
Once the entire group is activated, the selection orbs turn green,

14
00:00:24,112 --> 00:00:25,619
and those flowers are no longer interactive.

15
00:00:25,619 --> 00:00:27,772
The level doesn't tell the player what the goal is,

16
00:00:27,772 --> 00:00:30,786
leaving them to figure out that what allows them to proceed is matching BPMs.

17
00:00:30,786 --> 00:00:32,509
Further levels can be added based on harmony,

18
00:00:32,509 --> 00:00:35,523
and adding the challenge of optimizing the order in which the group is activated,

19
00:00:35,523 --> 00:00:40,044
if there's not enough time to physically get to all flowers in the group in arbitrary order because of space geometry.

20
00:00:40,044 --> 00:00:44,350
The player can brute-force the level by testing all flowers against a single one and seeing which play together well.

21
00:00:44,350 --> 00:00:46,933
However, the loop plays twice each time, forcing them to wait longer.

22
00:00:46,933 --> 00:00:50,378
If they listen to each flower once and figure out which ones match just by listening,

23
00:00:50,378 --> 00:00:52,100
they can collect the groups without time penalty.

24
00:00:52,100 --> 00:00:53,822
The time penalty, fail count limit, point scoring,

25
00:00:53,822 --> 00:00:56,621
and so on can be trivially added to encourage listening instead of brute-forcing.

26
00:00:56,621 --> 00:00:58,128
The level geometry is a Gaussian Splat,

27
00:00:58,128 --> 00:01:00,496
obtained from a world model generated with World Labs AI Marble,

28
00:01:00,496 --> 00:01:01,788
from a picture generated by Gemini,

29
00:01:01,788 --> 00:01:03,295
inspired by Buckminster Fuller's Dymaxion house architecture,

30
00:01:03,295 --> 00:01:05,017
and automatically segmented with Nigel Hartman's Splat Analyzer.

31
00:01:05,017 --> 00:01:07,601
The audio loops, as well as this voiceover, were generated by Claude.

32
00:01:07,601 --> 00:01:09,754
The source code was one hundred percent vibe-coded with Claude,

33
00:01:09,754 --> 00:01:12,337
based on the SensAI WebXR World Model template, built on Meta's IWER,

34
00:01:12,337 --> 00:01:14,705
during the SensAI Hack hackathon by XR Bootcamp, slash, SensAI Hackademy.

35
00:01:14,705 --> 00:01:18,365
The only thing made by a human in this project were prompts to various A Is: Gemini,

36
00:01:18,365 --> 00:01:19,226
World Labs, and Claude.
